{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}} {{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> | name = Don Raunikar | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = [[Psychotherapy|Psychotherapist]] | language = English | nationality = American | ethnicity = | citizenship = United States | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = ''Choosing God's Best'' | spouse = Kimberley Raunikar | partner = | children = Jonathan Valentin Raunikar | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | module = | website = <!-- www.example.com --> | portaldisp = }}
Dr. '''Don Raunikar''' is an American [[Psychoanalysis|psychoanalyst]] from [[Houston]], Texas.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Christianity Today]]|title=Kissing Nonsense Goodbye|author=Rob Marus|date=June 11, 2001|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2001/june11/6.46.html?start=2|accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref> He is a [[Baptists|Baptist]]<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Hamburger Abendblatt]]|title=Vor der Ehe nicht einmal ein Kuß|author=Barbara Driessen|date=March 14, 2006|url=http://www.abendblatt.de/politik/ausland/article385983/Vor-der-Ehe-nicht-einmal-ein-Kuss.html|accessdate=September 19, 2013|language=de}}</ref> and is married to Kim Raunikar, with whom he [[Adoption|adopted]] their son Jonathan Valentin from [[Romania]] through [[Buckner International]].<ref>{{Cite news|work=Baptist Standard|author=Russ Dilday|date=May 5, 2003|title=Buckner Adoption: Three of hearts|url=http://assets.baptiststandard.com/archived/2003/5_5/pages/buckner.html|accessdate=September 19, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921060717/http://assets.baptiststandard.com/archived/2003/5_5/pages/buckner.html|archivedate=September 21, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He is the director of New Life Clinics, where he practices [[psychotherapy]], and he is in charge of Lifehouse, a [[crisis pregnancy center]].<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Crosswalk.com]]|title=Making a "Good" Choice or a "God" Choice|date=February 3, 2005|url=http://www.crosswalk.com/family/singles/making-a-good-choice-or-a-god-choice-1311008.html?p=7|accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref> Raunikar advises singles not to engage in [[dating]] but instead to engage in [[Biblical courtship]], which he defines as an [[interpersonal relationship]] that honors God and in which both people's actions have the clear goal of pursuing marriage.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|title=More Couples Committed To Courtship As Alternative|author=Christine Tatum|date=February 25, 2000|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-02-25/news/0002250184_1_dating-singles-scene-marriage|accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref> He wrote the book ''Choosing God's Best: Wisdom for Lifelong Romance'', which was published in 1998.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Don Raunikar|title=Choosing God's Best: Wisdom for Lifelong Romance|year=1998|publisher=[[Random House]]|isbn=0307568652}}</ref> In this book, Raunikar writes that waiting for God's plan to unfold requires [[courage]] and [[faith]].<ref>{{Cite book|page=56|title=More Gems for the Journey|author=Vicki Johnson|publisher=[[Kimani Press]]|year=2006|isbn=1552545598}}</ref> Belinda Elliott of the [[Christian Broadcasting Network]] called ''Choosing God's Best'' her favorite book on Christian [[Romance (love)|romance]] and dating.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]]|title=Dating: God's Best or All the Rest?|author=Belinda Elliott|url=http://www.cbn.com/family/datingsingles/ElliottB_GodsBest.aspx|accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref> In the book ''The Invisible Bond: How to Break Free from Your Sexual Past'', Barbara Wilson writes that ''Choosing God's Best'' "resonated with [her] like none other" of the "many books on dating" she had read.<ref>{{Cite book|page=167|title=The Invisible Bond: How to Break Free from Your Sexual Past|author=Barbara Wilson|publisher=[[Random House]]|year=2010|isbn=0307562840}}</ref> In the journal ''Critical Research on Religion'', Courtney Ann Irby of [[Loyola University Chicago]] writes about the similarities between ''Choosing God's Best'' and other [[Evangelicalism|Evangelical]] books about premarital romantic relationships, such as [[Dannah Gresh]]'s ''And the Bride Wore White'', [[Elisabeth Elliot]]'s ''[[Passion and Purity]]'' and ''Quest for Love'', [[Eric Ludy|Eric]] and [[Leslie Ludy]]'s ''[[When God Writes Your Love Story]]'', Ben Young's and Sam Adams' ''The Ten Commandments of Dating'', Henry Cloud's and John Townsend's ''Boundaries in Dating'', Alex Chediak's ''5 Paths to the Love of Your Life'', and [[Joshua Harris (pastor)|Joshua Harris]]'s ''[[I Kissed Dating Goodbye]]'' and ''[[Boy Meets Girl: Say Hello to Courtship|Boy Meets Girl]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Irby, Courtney Ann|title='We didn't call it dating': The disrupted landscape of relationship advice for evangelical Protestant youth|page=180|journal=Critical Research on Religion|year=2013|volume=1|doi=10.1177/2050303213490041}}</ref>
