A '''dorsiventral''' (Lat. ''dorsum'', "the back", ''venter'', "the belly") [[Organ (anatomy)|organ]] is one that has two surfaces differing from each other in appearance and structure, as an ordinary [[leaf]].<ref>{{EB1911|wstitle=Dorsiventral |inline=1 |volume=8 |page=436}}</ref> This term has also been used as a synonym for [[dorsoventral]] organs, those that extend from a [[Dorsum (biology)|dorsal]] to a [[ventral]] surface.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}
This word is also used to define body structure of an organism, e.g. Platyhelminthes have dorsiventrally flattened body.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}}

